        "number": 4,
        "title": "The withering grass — futility as the enemies' destiny",
        "range": "129:6-7",
        "excerpt": "Let them be like grass upon the housetops, which withers before it grows up; with which the reaper does not fill his hand.",
        "body": "The psalm's controlling metaphor for the enemies' fate is drawn from the most ordinary feature of ancient Near Eastern architecture: the flat clay rooftop. After rain, grass sprouts in the thin film of soil on rooftops — a flash of green that disappears as quickly as it appeared. The soil is too shallow to hold moisture; the sun scorches it before it can mature. No one harvests rooftop grass. No reaper fills his hand; no binder fills his arms. It is not merely that the grass fails to reach its potential — it fails to reach any threshold of usefulness at all.\n\nThe image is carefully constructed to address the enemies of Zion at exactly the point where they would expect triumph. Ancient military power was measured in agricultural surplus — the ability to feed armies, pay tribute, produce wealth. The enemy who plows Israel's back (v. 3) is an enemy who expects a harvest. The psalm answers: your own life, your own power, your own projects, will be like rooftop grass — apparent vitality, no actual fruitfulness. The long furrows you plowed will not correspond to any harvest you receive.\n\nThe canonical background is dense. Isaiah 40:6-8 uses the identical grass-withering image for the transience of human power before the word of God ('the grass withers, the flower fades, but the word of our God stands forever'). Psalm 37:2 applies the same metaphor to the wicked more broadly: 'they will soon wither like the grass.' The Psalter has a settled theology of the wicked's futility — their apparent flourishing is always described as temporary, shallow-rooted, scorchable. Psalm 129 applies this theology specifically to the enemies of Zion.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Chatsir* (grass) — the word for cut grass or green vegetation; used in Isaiah 40:6-8 for the transience of human flesh. *Gag* (rooftop) — the flat roof of ancient mud-brick architecture. *Yavesh* (withers) — to dry out, be scorched; the same root as Isaiah 40:7 ('the grass withers'). *Qatser* (reaper) — the harvest worker; *immer* (binder of sheaves) — the one who gathers cut grain."
